description:
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Applications are invited from committed and enthusiastic doctors for the above post at St Mary’s and Queen Charlotte’s Hospital for 2 years with research exemption or 3 years without research exemption. The post has subspecialty approval from the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Candidates should have a demonstrable interest in Urogynaecology. Ideally the candidates should have undertaken a period of research in Urogynaecology.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Imperial College has one of the largest urogynaecology subspecialty units in the UK with tertiary and national referrals. The programme is well supported with multidisciplinary links to urology and colorectal services. There are strong academic and research ties with the Faculty of Medicine, Imperial College London. Imperial College Healthcare NHS trust is an approved centre for the treatment of complex pelvic floor and urinary/faecal incontinence. The centre is approved for the treatment of urinary incontinence with sacral nerve stimulation. It has applied to be a centre for the treatment of mesh complications&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The appointed doctor will continue 3rd on call cover for obstetrics and gynaecology out of hours.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Applicants must have MRCOG part 2 and should have finished specialty training year 5 or have CCT.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please apply on-line for this post. Only online applications will be considered&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further information please contact the following Professor Khullar contactable through vik.khullar@imperial.ac.uk or Mr Fernando through ruwan.fernando@nhs.net or Mr Digesu through a.digesu@nhs.net&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
